Building energy semantic net (BESN) Structure

The connection matrices of ESN layers are shown in Table 3. The connection matrices is a direct mapping of ESN schematic shown in Fig. 6. Connection cells with value of 1 is replaced by the parameter variable (pji)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(p_{j}^{i})$$\end{document} for those classes with design parameters at any layer that are connected to previous layer classes. The parameter p14\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p_{1}^{4}$$\end{document} at layer four represent the penetration of DC power demand as a percentage of the total power demand. This parameter characterizes the replacement of AC loads percentage to DC (such as lighting). Hence, a scenario at which reduction of energy conversion losses from DC (output of PV panel) to AC will be investigated. In addition, the potential of reducing capital cost due to reducing the DC/AC inverter size will be examined. At the same layer, thermal zones are connected to heat demand and both connection cells have the same parameter (p34)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(p_{3}^{4})$$\end{document} which is an application of point (2) of ESN algorithm stated in “Building Energy Semantic Network Structure” section. p34\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p_{3}^{4}$$\end{document} is a parameter representing the variation of aggregate heat demand of the house due to variation of thermal zone configuration. The parameter can be moved upward one layer and split to two parameters associated with each thermal zone. However, because the thermal simulation conducted outside ESN algorithm using EnergyPlus, the parameter was considered to select between two different heat demand profiles achieved by EnergyPlus simulation of the two thermal zone scenarios. Moreover, thermal zone configuration affect economic and environmental KPI through heat demand reduction only. For other energy conservation measure, such as changing insulation materials, the economic KPI is affected by both heat demand reduction and materials’ prices. Hence the parameters should be placed on the proper layer with proper definition.

The DC/AC inverter and AC/DC converter sizes as a percentage of PV size and WT size and are presented by p15\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
