				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p_{8}^{5}$$\end{document} represent PV and WT area respectively (hence, their size is identified as a design parameter). The electrical heater size is a percentage of total power demand while the micro-CHP gas generator and the furnace size is in kW.

The selection vectors of ESN layers is shown in Table 4. It can be noted that residential class was selected at layer one and house class was selected at layer two. The rest selection vectors indicates the selection of all house sub-classes and energy sources’ classes. Some of energy classes are not identified in this ESN [energy storage classes (batteries and thermal storage)] to introduce simple and clear implementation of proposed ESN algorithm. The connection matrices should present all energy technologies and buildings classes. The designer should use the selection vectors to implement the energy concept of the building under investigation. For example, if the concept is not to include WT as an energy source then s85\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {s}_{8}^{5}$$\end{document} will be reset to zero.

